Security Philosophy: Lab Mapping & The CIA Triad
My security philosophy for this project is built upon the CIA Triad, which I have mapped to this specific lab environment:

Confidentiality: I have implemented this by setting my GitHub repository to Private. This ensures that only authorized individuals (myself and my instructor) can view the contents of my workbench.

Integrity: I am using Git Version Control to maintain the integrity of my work. Each commit provides a unique hash and timestamp, ensuring that my documentation remains accurate and that any changes are tracked and verified.

Availability: By pushing my local iMac files to GitHub’s cloud-based platform, I ensure that my work is available even if I experience a local hardware failure. This redundancy guarantees access to my technical deliverables whenever needed.

Security Foundations: Governance & Frameworks
AAA Framework
The AAA Framework manages how I interact with this technical environment:

Authentication: Verifying my identity through my GitHub username and Personal Access Token (PAT).

Authorization: The specific permissions granted to my account to "write" and modify this repository.

Accounting: The use of Git logs to record every update I make, creating a professional audit trail.

Governance in Cybersecurity
Governance represents the rules and oversight that align technical work with business goals. In cybersecurity, governance ensures that technical teams follow established frameworks (like NIST or CIS) to remain compliant with laws and regulations. It provides the "Security Blueprint" that guides every technical decision I make.

Reflection
Governance is just as important as technical skill because it provides the "why" and "how" for security. While a technical skill allows me to create a repository, governance ensures that the repository is auditable, secure, and compliant with professional standards. Without these frameworks, technical security would be disorganized and difficult to verify. The cybersecurity domain that aligns most with today’s material is GRC (Governance, Risk, and Compliance). This lab specifically highlights the "Compliance" and "Accounting" aspects of maintaining a professional technical workbench.

